But the user says "immediately slow down" — NOT "instantaneously stop." The key words are "not continue moving." The piston doesn't instantly stop — it takes time to decelerate. But during that deceleration, the exhaust chamber is still being compressed (though more slowly).
So CAN P_exhaust reach 60 bar? Let's see:
At P_exhaust = 2 bar (equal to P_supply), direction=+1:
F_pressure = 0
F_spring = 0 (assuming outside spring zone)
F_friction = -70 N
F_net = -70 N
a = -70/5.5 = -12.7 m/s²
At v=0.07 m/s: stopping time = 0.07/12.7 = 0.0055 s
Stopping distance = 0.07²/(2*12.7) = 0.00019 m = 0.19 mm
During this 0.19 mm of forward travel, the exhaust volume decreases by 0.00019 * A = 1.34e-7 m³.
If the exhaust volume before deceleration was, say, 0.01 * A = 7.07e-6 m³ (at x = 0.29 m):
The volume after stopping is 7.07e-6 - 1.34e-7 = 6.94e-6 m³
The volume ratio is 7.07/6.94 = 1.02, so P_exhaust increases by 2%.
So if P_exhaust was 2 bar when deceleration started, it reaches about 2.04 bar when the piston stops. NOT 60 bar.
This confirms the user is RIGHT — 60 bar is NOT physically possible with correct physics.
So WHY does the simulation produce 60 bar (or fail trying to)?
